output:
Three bugs:

1. No start-byte validation. PMS5003 frames always start with 0x42, 0x4D. Without checking, you may be reading mid-frame and getting garbage offsets.

2. Wrong byte offsets. In the raw 32-byte frame, PM2.5 (atmospheric) is at buf[8] and buf[9] — not buf[4]/buf[5]. Bytes 4-5 are PM1.0 standard, 6-7 are PM2.5 standard, 8-9 are PM2.5 atmospheric.

3. No availability check before read. If fewer than 32 bytes are available, readBytes() returns partial data.

Fixed loop:
  if (pms.available() >= 32) {
    uint8_t buf[32];
    pms.readBytes(buf, 32);
    if (buf[0] == 0x42 && buf[1] == 0x4D) {
      uint16_t pm25 = (buf[8] << 8) | buf[9]; // atmospheric PM2.5
      Serial.println(pm25);
    }
  }

