The MH-Z19B sends a 9-byte response frame. The last byte (byte[8]) is a checksum used to verify data integrity during transmission.

Checksum calculation:
1. Take bytes 1 through 7 (indices 1–7, skipping the start byte 0xFF)
2. Sum them all
3. Take the bitwise complement of the lower 8 bits: (~sum) & 0xFF
4. Add 1: result = ((~sum) & 0xFF) + 1

If the received byte[8] matches this calculation, the frame is valid. If not, the data was corrupted during UART transmission.

Example in code:
  byte checksum = 0;
  for (int i = 1; i < 8; i++) checksum += response[i];
  checksum = (~checksum) + 1;
  if (checksum != response[8]) {
    Serial.println("Checksum error — discard reading");
    return -1;
  }

Always validate before using the CO2 value.

