Critical limitation: Arduino's SoftwareSerial library can only actively listen on ONE instance at a time. When you call read or readBytes on one, the other is not listening and misses incoming bytes — resulting in empty or garbage buffers.

Fix: Use the listen() method to switch between instances, but be aware that while one is listening, the other DROPS incoming data. This only works if the sensors send data at intervals (not continuously).

For PMS5003 (sends every 1 second) + MH-Z19 (responds only when polled):

  void loop() {
    // Read PMS5003 (it sends continuously)
    pms.listen();
    delay(1100); // wait for a full frame
    uint8_t buf[32];
    if (pms.available() >= 32) pms.readBytes(buf, 32);

    // Switch to CO2 and poll
    co2.listen();
    co2.write(co2Cmd, 9);
    delay(150);
    byte r[9];
    if (co2.available() >= 9) co2.readBytes(r, 9);

    delay(3000);
  }

Better long-term solution: Use an Arduino Mega (4 hardware UARTs), or an ESP32 (3 hardware UARTs) to eliminate SoftwareSerial entirely.

