BUG FOUND: `DDRB = 0x00;` sets ALL Port B pins as INPUT, so PB5 cannot drive the LED.

FIX:
```c
#include <avr/io.h>
#include <util/delay.h>

int main(void) {
    DDRB = (1 << DDB5);  // ✅ Set PB5 as OUTPUT only
    while(1) {
        PORTB = (1 << PORTB5);
        _delay_ms(1000);
        PORTB = 0x00;
        _delay_ms(1000);
    }
}
```

Bit-level explanation:
- `DDRB = 0x00` → 0b00000000 → all pins INPUT (wrong)
- `DDRB = (1 << DDB5)` → 0b00100000 → only PB5 is OUTPUT (correct)

Tip: Always use `|=` instead of `=` when setting individual bits to avoid accidentally clearing other pins:
`DDRB |= (1 << DDB5);`  ← safer approach

```c
#include <avr/io.h>
#include <util/delay.h>

int main(void) {
    // Setup
    DDRB  |= (1 << DDB0);    // PB0 as OUTPUT (LED)
    DDRD  &= ~(1 << DDD2);   // PD2 as INPUT (Button)
    PORTD |= (1 << PORTD2);  // Enable internal pull-up on PD2

    uint8_t led_state = 0;

    while (1) {
        // Button pressed when pin reads LOW (active-low with pull-up)
        if (!(PIND & (1 << PIND2))) {
            _delay_ms(20);  // Debounce delay
            if (!(PIND & (1 << PIND2))) {
                led_state ^= 1;  // Toggle LED state
                if (led_state) {
                    PORTB |= (1 << PORTB0);   // LED ON
                } else {
                    PORTB &= ~(1 << PORTB0);  // LED OFF
                }
                // Wait for button release
                while (!(PIND & (1 << PIND2)));
            }
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Key points:
- `PIND` is the PIN Input Register — use it to READ the state of Port D pins.
- `PORTD |= (1 << PORTD2)` enables the internal ~20–50kΩ pull-up resistor.
- When button is pressed, PD2 is pulled to GND → reads as 0 (active-low).
- XOR (`^= 1`) toggles the LED state variable each press.
- Debounce prevents false triggers from mechanical bounce.

