output:
THREE BUGS FOUND:

BUG 1 — No ADC clock prescaler set:
The ADC requires a clock between 50kHz and 200kHz for 10-bit resolution. Without setting ADPS bits, the ADC runs at full CPU frequency (e.g., 16MHz), which exceeds the max and causes incorrect readings (extreme values: 0 or 1023).

BUG 2 — Reading only ADCH instead of full 10-bit ADC result:
`ADCH` alone gives only the upper 8 bits. For 10-bit results you need the `ADC` macro (which reads ADCL first, then ADCH automatically). If ADLAR=0 (right-justified, default), ADCH only has bits 9:8 — reading it without ADCL first gives garbage.

BUG 3 — ADC not re-triggered after first conversion:
Setting ADSC once in init starts ONE conversion. In `adc_read()`, you must re-trigger ADSC before waiting.

FIXED CODE:
```c
void adc_init(void) {
    // REFS0=1: AVCC reference
    // No ADLAR bit: right-justified result
    // MUX3:0 = 0000: channel 0 (PC0)
    ADMUX = (1 << REFS0);

    // ADEN=1: Enable ADC
    // ADPS2:0 = 111: Prescaler /128 → 16MHz/128 = 125kHz ✅
    ADCSRA = (1 << ADEN)
           | (1 << ADPS2)
           | (1 << ADPS1)
           | (1 << ADPS0);

    // Dummy first conversion (ADC needs warm-up read)
    ADCSRA |= (1 << ADSC);
    while (ADCSRA & (1 << ADSC));
}

uint16_t adc_read(uint8_t channel) {
    // Select channel
    ADMUX = (ADMUX & 0xF0) | (channel & 0x0F);

    // Start conversion
    ADCSRA |= (1 << ADSC);         // ✅ Trigger new conversion
    while (ADCSRA & (1 << ADSC));  // Wait for ADSC to clear

    return ADC;  // ✅ Read full 10-bit result (ADCL + ADCH)
}
```

