Yes, the order matters, and this is actually a subtle bug. servo.write() before servo.attach() sets an internal angle variable in the Servo object, but no PWM signal is sent because the pin hasn't been attached yet. On most Arduino Servo library versions, calling write() before attach() is a no-op for the hardware — the servo doesn't actually move to 70 degrees at power-on. The correct sequence is: servo.attach(3) first, then servo.write(70). This ensures the servo physically moves to the neutral 70-degree position before the main loop starts. Fix the order in setup():

