The color is stored as a 24-bit integer where the upper 8 bits are red, the middle 8 bits are green, and the lower 8 bits are blue:

  int r = (color & 0xFF0000) >> 16;
  int g = (color & 0xFF00)   >> 8;
  int b = (color & 0xFF);

For 0x007582:
  r = (0x007582 & 0xFF0000) >> 16 = 0x000000 >> 16 = 0
  g = (0x007582 & 0x00FF00) >> 8  = 0x007500 >> 8  = 0x75 = 117
  b = (0x007582 & 0x0000FF)       = 0x000082        = 0x82 = 130

So the pixel is set to RGB(0, 117, 130), a teal colour. Bitmasking isolates each byte and the right-shift moves it into the 0–255 range.

