Bug: lockServo.write(90) is called on every single iteration of loop(), which runs thousands of times per second. This continuously sends PWM commands to the servo, causing it to twitch, draw excess current, and potentially wear out faster.

Fix: Only write to the servo when the position actually needs to change. Set the servo position once in setup() and only call write() again when intentionally unlocking or re-locking:

void setup() {
  lockServo.attach(SERVO_PIN);
  lockServo.write(90);  // Set to locked position once at startup
  // Never call write() in loop() unless changing position
}

void loop() {
  char key = keypad.getKey();
  if (key == '#') {
    processPassword();  // write() is only called here, intentionally
  }
  // No lockServo.write() here
}

Additionally, if servo jitter persists even when write() is not being called, it may be due to electrical noise on the PWM line. Adding a 100µF capacitor between the servo's VCC and GND wires, and ensuring the servo is powered from a stable 5V source (not the Arduino's 5V pin under heavy load), can resolve this.

