**Bug: Using `if` instead of `else if` for the conditional chain.**

**Problem:**
Each condition block uses an independent `if` statement. This means ALL conditions are evaluated every loop iteration. If the first `if` block runs and changes motor state, and the second `if` also happens to evaluate true, it will immediately override the first block in the same loop cycle — causing conflicting or undefined motor behavior. In practice with only two `if` blocks here, the robot ends up only going forward because the conditions are not mutually exclusive when evaluated sequentially without `else`.

**Additionally:** Only two of the four cases are handled (forward and turn-right). Turn-left and stop are missing.

**Fix:** Use `if / else if / else if / else` to make conditions mutually exclusive, and add all four cases:
```cpp
void loop(){
  if(digitalRead(left)==0 && digitalRead(right)==0){
    // Forward
    motor1.run(FORWARD); motor1.setSpeed(150);
    motor2.run(FORWARD); motor2.setSpeed(150);
