**Bug: Using OR (`||`) instead of AND (`&&`) for the stop condition.**

**Problem:**
The stop condition `digitalRead(left)==1 || digitalRead(right)==1` triggers whenever **either** sensor reads 1 (HIGH / off-line). This means if one sensor detects the line (reads 0) and the other is off-line (reads 1), the robot will still stop instead of turning.

This overlaps with the turn conditions, so the stop block fires prematurely — during normal turning, one sensor reads 1, triggering the stop before the turn can execute.

The robot appears to never stop on a fully black surface because: if this stop block runs first in the conditional chain (e.g., as a top-level `if` instead of the last `else`), the turn cases below it may never be reached.

**Fix:** Use AND (`&&`) — the robot should stop only when **both** sensors read 1 (completely off the line):
```cpp
if(digitalRead(left)==1 && digitalRead(right)==1){
  motor1.run(RELEASE); motor1.setSpeed(0);
  motor2.run(RELEASE); motor2.setSpeed(0);
  motor3.run(RELEASE); motor3.setSpeed(0);
  motor4.run(RELEASE); motor4.setSpeed(0);
}
```

**Also:** Make sure this is the final `else` block in the if-else chain, not a standalone `if`, to prevent it from running simultaneously with other conditions.

