The function only checks the first byte of CONFIG_VERSION ('V') but the full version string is 5 characters ('V','E','R','0','1'). If any byte after the first is corrupted or uninitialized, the struct would still be loaded with potentially bad data — but more critically, if the first byte check fails (e.g., on a fresh board), all bytes are ignored.

The original code checks all 5 version bytes, which is the correct approach:

int loadConfig() {
  if (EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + 0) == CONFIG_VERSION[0] &&
      EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + 1) == CONFIG_VERSION[1] &&
      EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + 2) == CONFIG_VERSION[2] &&
      EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + 3) == CONFIG_VERSION[3] &&
      EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + 4) == CONFIG_VERSION[4]) {
    for (unsigned int i = 0; i < sizeof(CONFIGURATION); i++)
      *((char*)&CONFIGURATION + i) = EEPROM.read(CONFIG_START + i);
    return 1;
  }
  return 0;
}

Also make sure saveConfig() writes CONFIGURATION.displaycolor, .brightness, and .microphone before calling the write loop.

This is a mode-mismatch bug. The free-running ADC mode (ADCSRA = 0b11100101, ADMUX = 0b00000000) is only configured in setup() when microphone == 0 (audio-in mode). If the EEPROM loads microphone = 1 (mic mode) but the Sampling() function (which expects free-running ADC) is somehow called, the ADC will not be ready and the while(!(ADCSRA & 0x10)) loop will spin indefinitely or read garbage, causing severe display issues.

Fix: Ensure the loop() correctly routes to SamplingMic() when microphone == 1 and to Sampling() when microphone == 0:

void loop() {
  while (1) {
    if (microphone) {
      SamplingMic();
    } else {
      Sampling();
    }
    // ...
  }
}

Also confirm that the ADCSRA/ADMUX initialization block in setup() is inside the if (!microphone) guard, not executing unconditionally.

The bug is a shared previousState variable. Both colorChange() and brightnessChange() read and write the same global previousState byte. When colorChange() runs and sets previousState = reading from colorPIN, the next call to brightnessChange() compares its reading against the wrong previous value — the one written by colorChange(). This can cause false edge detections and double-increments.

Fix: Use separate previousState variables for each button:

