The x-axis flip is missing. In the original hardware layout, the DIN connector is on the right side, meaning LED 0 is at the bottom-right, not the bottom-left. The first column of the display (x=0) is physically the rightmost column.

Without the flip line x = xres - x - 1, column 0 of your display data maps to the rightmost physical column, column 1 to the second-from-right, and so on — the whole spectrum appears mirrored left-to-right.

Fix:
int GetLedFromMatrix(byte x, byte y) {
  int led;
  x = xres - x - 1; // <-- flip x to account for DIN on right side
  if (x & 0x01) {
    led = ((x + 1) * yres - y - 1);
  } else {
    led = ((x + 1) * yres - yres + y);
  }
  return constrain(led, 0, NUM_LEDS);
}

The constrain() call is also important to prevent writing to LED indices outside the strip bounds, which can cause undefined behavior or corrupt neighboring pixel data.

