const int LED_PIN = 9;
int brightness = 0;
int fadeAmount = 5;
unsigned long previousMillis = 0;
const long interval = 30;

void setup() {
  pinMode(LED_PIN, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  unsigned long currentMillis = millis();
  if (currentMillis - previousMillis >= interval) {
    previousMillis = currentMillis;
    analogWrite(LED_PIN, brightness);
    brightness += fadeAmount;
    if (brightness <= 0 || brightness >= 255) {
      fadeAmount = -fadeAmount;
      brightness = constrain(brightness, 0, 255);
    }
  }
  // Other non-blocking code can run here
}

delay() is a blocking function — the Arduino processor halts completely for the specified duration. During a delay(1000), the program cannot read sensors, check buttons, update displays, or do anything else. This makes it impossible to run multiple tasks 'simultaneously'.

millis() returns the number of milliseconds since the Arduino started running. By storing the last time a task ran and comparing it to the current millis() value, you can execute tasks at timed intervals WITHOUT halting the processor:

if (millis() - lastRun >= interval) {
  lastRun = millis();
  // do timed task
}

This is the Arduino equivalent of a non-blocking timer. Benefits:
- Multiple timed tasks can run at different intervals in the same loop()
- Buttons and sensors remain responsive
- Critical tasks (safety checks, communication) are not blocked

Limitation: millis() overflows after ~49.7 days (wraps back to 0). The subtraction method (currentMillis - previousMillis) handles overflow correctly because unsigned integer subtraction wraps around properly.

