int ledState = LOW;
unsigned long previousMillis;
const long interval = 1000;
void setup() { pinMode(13, OUTPUT); }
void loop() {
  if (millis() - previousMillis >= interval) {
    ledState = !ledState;
    digitalWrite(13, ledState);
    previousMillis = millis();
  }
}

output:
The bug is that previousMillis is updated with millis() AFTER the interval check, but millis() advances by a tiny amount between the if check and the assignment. More importantly, previousMillis is not initialized, so it starts at 0 and the very first check fires immediately — which is fine. The real issue to watch for is if previousMillis = millis() is called AFTER the check, the previous timestamp advances to a slightly later time, causing a small accumulated timing drift.

A more subtle bug: if ledState is an int (not bool), the line ledState = !ledState may not toggle reliably for all values. Use boolean or explicitly write:
ledState = (ledState == LOW) ? HIGH : LOW;

Best practice fix:
void loop() {
  unsigned long currentMillis = millis();
  if (currentMillis - previousMillis >= interval) {
    previousMillis = currentMillis; // capture SAME timestamp
    ledState = (ledState == LOW) ? HIGH : LOW;
    digitalWrite(13, ledState);
  }
}

