When you press a physical button, the metal contacts don't make a clean single connection — they bounce rapidly (make and break contact multiple times) over 1-20ms before settling. This mechanical bouncing causes the Arduino to register multiple button presses per single physical press.

For example, pressing once might be read as 5-50 rapid presses, triggering code multiple times unintentionally — a dice might roll 3 times instead of once.

Debounce methods:

1. Software delay debounce: After detecting a state change, wait 10-50ms and re-read the pin. If the state is the same, it's a real press:
if (currentState != lastState) {
  delay(50);
  if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == currentState) {
    // confirmed press
  }
}

2. Millis-based debounce (non-blocking):
Store the time of last state change. Only process if enough time has passed since last change.

3. Hardware debounce: Add a 0.1µF capacitor between the button pin and GND to physically filter the bounce signal.

The Bounce2 library provides a clean, easy-to-use software debounce implementation.

