input:
for (int u = 0; u < NUM_USERS; u++) {
  if (rfid.uid.uidByte == KNOWN_UIDS[u]) {
    Serial.println("Match!");
  }
}

output:
The bug is the UID comparison: rfid.uid.uidByte == KNOWN_UIDS[u] compares two array pointers (memory addresses), not the actual array contents. In C/C++, you cannot compare arrays with ==; it compares their addresses, which are always different, so the comparison is always false.

Fix: Compare each byte individually using a loop:
bool match = true;
for (int b = 0; b < 4; b++) {
  if (rfid.uid.uidByte[b] != KNOWN_UIDS[u][b]) {
    match = false;
    break;
  }
}
if (match) {
  Serial.println("Match!");
}

Alternatively, use memcmp():
if (memcmp(rfid.uid.uidByte, KNOWN_UIDS[u], 4) == 0) {
  Serial.println("Match!");
}
memcmp() returns 0 when two memory regions are identical.

