PSRAM (Pseudo-Static RAM) is an external SPI RAM chip soldered onto most ESP32-CAM modules, providing an additional 4MB of RAM beyond the ESP32's internal 520KB SRAM.

Why it matters for camera:
- JPEG frames at higher resolutions (SVGA 800×600, XGA, UXGA 1600×1200) can be hundreds of kilobytes each. Internal SRAM alone cannot hold these.
- PSRAM allows the DMA framebuffer allocator to store full-resolution JPEG images.

In code, the `psramFound()` check gates the frame size and buffer count:
```cpp
if (psramFound()) {
  config.frame_size   = FRAMESIZE_QVGA; // up to UXGA possible
  config.jpeg_quality = 10;             // lower = better quality
  config.fb_count     = 2;             // double buffering
} else {
  config.frame_size   = FRAMESIZE_SVGA;
  config.jpeg_quality = 12;
  config.fb_count     = 1;             // single buffer only
}
```

`fb_count = 2` enables double buffering: while one frame is being displayed or transmitted, the camera is filling the second buffer — increasing throughput and reducing tearing artifacts.

To verify PSRAM is enabled in Arduino IDE:
- Go to Tools → PSRAM → Enabled.
- Without this setting, `psramFound()` returns false even if PSRAM is physically present, and `ps_malloc()` calls will fail silently.

