The root cause is the blocking `delay(30000)` preventing `mqtt.loop()` from being called frequently enough.

How MQTT keepalive works: the MQTT protocol sends a PINGREQ packet to the broker at regular intervals (default 15 seconds in PubSubClient). The broker expects a PINGREQ within the keepalive window; if it does not receive one, it assumes the client is dead and drops the connection.

When `delay(30000)` blocks the CPU for 30 seconds, `mqtt.loop()` is never called during that window — so no PINGREQ is sent — and the broker terminates the connection.

Fix — use non-blocking timing:
```cpp
unsigned long lastPublish = 0;
const unsigned long PUBLISH_INTERVAL = 30000;

void loop() {
  if (!mqtt.connected()) connectMQTT();
  mqtt.loop(); // MUST be called every iteration, never block this

  if (millis() - lastPublish >= PUBLISH_INTERVAL) {
    lastPublish = millis();
    // publish sensor data here
    mqtt.publish("home/sensor", "value");
  }
  // Do NOT use delay() here
}
```

Alternatively, extend the keepalive timer:
```cpp
mqtt.setKeepAlive(60); // seconds — set before connect()
```
But the non-blocking `millis()` pattern is the proper solution.

