These three modes control how an ESP32 GPIO pin reads digital signals:

**INPUT**: The pin is a high-impedance floating input with no internal resistor. If nothing is connected, the pin 'floats' and reads random HIGH/LOW values due to electromagnetic noise. This is why a physical external pull-up or pull-down resistor (typically 10kΩ) is required when using plain INPUT. In the uploaded code, the button on GPIO4 uses `INPUT`, which means the circuit must provide a pull-down resistor to ensure the pin reads LOW when the button is not pressed.

**INPUT_PULLUP**: Activates an internal ~45kΩ pull-up resistor to 3.3V. The pin reads HIGH when nothing is connected or when the button is open. When the button connects the pin to GND, it reads LOW. Button logic is inverted — pressing = LOW. This is the most common and safest mode for buttons since no external resistor is needed:
```cpp
pinMode(buttonPin, INPUT_PULLUP);
// Button reads LOW when pressed
if (digitalRead(buttonPin) == LOW) { /* pressed */ }
```

**INPUT_PULLDOWN**: Activates an internal pull-down resistor to GND. The pin reads LOW when floating. It reads HIGH when a voltage source is applied. Useful when the button connects to 3.3V rather than GND:
```cpp
pinMode(buttonPin, INPUT_PULLDOWN);
// Button reads HIGH when pressed
if (digitalRead(buttonPin) == HIGH) { /* pressed */ }
```

For the project in question, replacing `INPUT` with `INPUT_PULLDOWN` would eliminate the need for an external pull-down resistor.

