void onWrite(BLECharacteristic *pCharacteristic) {
  std::string value = pCharacteristic->getValue();
  if (value.length() > 0) {
    for (int i = 0; i < value.length(); i++)
      Serial.print(value[i]);
  }
}

output:
`pCharacteristic->getValue()` retrieves the raw byte data that was most recently written to this BLE characteristic by a connected client. It returns a `std::string`, which in this context acts as a byte buffer (not necessarily UTF-8 text, though it often contains ASCII).

`value.length()` returns the number of bytes written. Checking `> 0` guards against empty writes.

The for loop iterates over each byte and prints it via `Serial.print()`. Since `Serial.print(char)` prints the ASCII character, this works correctly for text data.

For binary data (e.g., a 4-byte float), you would instead cast or memcpy the raw bytes:
```cpp
if (value.length() == 4) {
  float f;
  memcpy(&f, value.data(), 4);
  Serial.println(f);
}
```

Note: In newer versions of the ESP32 Arduino BLE library, `getValue()` may return `String` instead of `std::string`, so check the library version.

