NVS (Non-Volatile Storage) is a key-value store built into the ESP32 flash. Unlike SPIFFS or LittleFS, NVS stores individual typed values rather than files, and it is optimized for frequent writes (it handles wear leveling internally).

Common use cases: storing WiFi credentials, user settings, counters, calibration data.

Example — write and read an integer:
```cpp
#include <Preferences.h>
Preferences prefs;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);

  prefs.begin("myapp", false);  // namespace, false = read/write
  int count = prefs.getInt("bootCount", 0);
  count++;
  prefs.putInt("bootCount", count);
  prefs.end();

  Serial.println("Boot count: " + String(count));
}
```

`prefs.begin("myapp", false)` opens a namespace. Namespaces let different parts of an app store keys without collisions.
`prefs.getInt(key, defaultValue)` reads a key; returns the default if not found.
`prefs.putInt(key, value)` writes the value.
`prefs.end()` closes the namespace and flushes the data.

Supported types include: Int, UInt, Long, Float, Double, Bool, String, Bytes.

