void IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() {
  Serial.println("Button pressed!");
}
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  pinMode(0, INPUT_PULLUP);
  attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(0), buttonISR, FALLING);
}

output:
This is the classic switch debounce problem. Mechanical buttons produce multiple rapid transitions (bounces) when pressed or released, each triggering the ISR.

Two fixes:

1. Software debounce in the ISR using a timestamp:
```cpp
volatile unsigned long lastPressTime = 0;

void IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() {
  unsigned long now = millis();
  if (now - lastPressTime > 200) {  // 200ms debounce window
    lastPressTime = now;
    // Set a flag — avoid Serial.println inside ISR!
    buttonPressed = true;
  }
}
```

2. Use a flag in the ISR and handle the action in loop():
```cpp
volatile bool buttonPressed = false;

void IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() { buttonPressed = true; }

void loop() {
  if (buttonPressed) {
    buttonPressed = false;
    Serial.println("Button pressed!");  // safe outside ISR
  }
}
```

Note: `Serial.println()` inside an ISR is unsafe on ESP32 — it can cause WDT resets or corrupted output. Always use a flag and handle output in `loop()`.

