The ESP32 runs FreeRTOS and has two cores (Core 0 and Core 1). By default, `loop()` runs on Core 1 and the WiFi/BLE stack runs on Core 0.

You can create additional FreeRTOS tasks with `xTaskCreatePinnedToCore()` to run code truly in parallel:

```cpp
void taskA(void* parameter) {
  for (;;) {
    Serial.println("Task A on Core 0");
    vTaskDelay(1000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);
  }
}

void taskB(void* parameter) {
  for (;;) {
    Serial.println("Task B on Core 1");
    vTaskDelay(2000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);
  }
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(taskA, "TaskA", 10000, NULL, 1, NULL, 0);
  xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(taskB, "TaskB", 10000, NULL, 1, NULL, 1);
}

void loop() {}
```

Arguments to `xTaskCreatePinnedToCore`: function, name, stack size (bytes), parameter, priority, handle pointer, core ID.

Use `vTaskDelay()` instead of `delay()` inside tasks — it yields the CPU to other tasks rather than blocking the core. Always use a `for(;;)` infinite loop inside task functions.

