The ESP32 has three hardware UART interfaces: Serial (UART0, used for programming/debug), Serial1 (UART1), and Serial2 (UART2).

Serial2 uses GPIO16 (RX) and GPIO17 (TX) by default, but any GPIO can be remapped.

Example — reading NMEA sentences from a GPS module (e.g., NEO-6M at 9600 baud):
```cpp
#define GPS_RX 16  // ESP32 RX ← GPS TX
#define GPS_TX 17  // ESP32 TX → GPS RX

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);    // debug output
  Serial2.begin(9600, SERIAL_8N1, GPS_RX, GPS_TX);
  Serial.println("GPS Serial2 ready");
}

void loop() {
  while (Serial2.available()) {
    char c = Serial2.read();
    Serial.write(c);  // echo to debug serial
  }
}
```

Wiring: GPS TX → ESP32 GPIO16, GPS RX → ESP32 GPIO17, GPS GND → ESP32 GND, GPS VCC → 3.3V or 5V depending on module.

For full NMEA parsing, use the TinyGPS++ library which parses latitude, longitude, speed, and time from the NMEA stream automatically.

