The issue is that `setValue()` accepts a `std::string` or `uint8_t*` buffer. Passing a plain `int` to `setValue()` does NOT convert it to a string — it may overload to the `uint8_t*` version and write a pointer address, producing garbage or an empty/incorrect result.

Fix depending on what you want the client to receive:

Option 1 — Send as ASCII string (readable by nRF Connect, phone apps):
```cpp
pCharacteristic->setValue(String(sensorValue).c_str());
```

Option 2 — Send as raw bytes (4-byte int for binary parsing):
```cpp
uint8_t bytes[4];
memcpy(bytes, &sensorValue, sizeof(sensorValue));
pCharacteristic->setValue(bytes, sizeof(bytes));
```

Option 3 — Use formatted string:
```cpp
char buf[20];
snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%d", sensorValue);
pCharacteristic->setValue(buf);
```

