The ESP32 has two Xtensa LX6 32-bit cores: Core 0 (Protocol CPU) and Core 1 (Application CPU). By default, Arduino code runs on Core 1. You can run tasks on Core 0 using FreeRTOS with xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(). Example:

void task0(void *param) {
  while(1) {
    Serial.println("Running on Core 0");
    vTaskDelay(1000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);
  }
}
void task1(void *param) {
  while(1) {
    Serial.println("Running on Core 1");
    vTaskDelay(1000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);
  }
}
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(task0, "Task0", 10000, NULL, 1, NULL, 0);
  xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(task1, "Task1", 10000, NULL, 1, NULL, 1);
}
void loop() {}

Core 0 handles Wi-Fi and Bluetooth stacks internally. Use Core 1 for user application tasks to avoid interference.

