output:
The garbled output is caused by a **baud rate mismatch**. The ESP32 boot ROM outputs at 115200 baud. If your code uses 9600 and your Serial Monitor is set to 115200 (or vice versa), you'll see garbage characters.

**Root cause:** The ESP32 first outputs boot messages at 115200 baud, then your code switches to 9600. The Serial Monitor receives these mixed baud rates as unreadable characters.

**Fix — Always use 115200 on ESP32:**
```cpp
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200); // match this in Arduino IDE Serial Monitor
  delay(1000); // wait for Serial to initialize
  Serial.println("Hello ESP32!");
}
void loop() {
  Serial.println("Running...");
  delay(1000);
}
```

**Also check:**
1. Arduino IDE Serial Monitor baud rate (bottom right dropdown) must match `Serial.begin()`.
2. Some USB-Serial adapters default to 115200 — always match.
3. If you see `ets Jul 29 2019` before garbled text, those are ESP32 boot messages — normal.
4. If using `Serial2` or `Serial1`, baud rate doesn't affect Serial Monitor unless you read and relay.

