input:
void loop() {
  String data = "";
  for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    data += String(i) + ",";
  }
  Serial.println(data.length());
  delay(100);
}

output:
While the `String` object in this specific loop is locally scoped and theoretically freed each iteration, the real issue is **heap fragmentation** from repeated String concatenation. Each `+=` operation potentially allocates a new, larger heap block and copies the old data.

**Heap fragmentation pattern:**
- 1000 iterations of `+=` = ~1000 malloc/realloc calls per loop() iteration
- Even if freed, the heap becomes fragmented with small unusable gaps
- Over time `ESP.getFreeHeap()` drops until allocation fails and ESP32 crashes

**Fix 1 – Pre-allocate String:**
```cpp
void loop() {
  String data;
  data.reserve(6000); // reserve estimated size upfront
  for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    data += String(i);
    data += ",";
  }
  Serial.println(data.length());
  Serial.println("Free heap: " + String(ESP.getFreeHeap()));
  delay(100);
}
```

**Fix 2 – Use char buffer (best practice):**
```cpp
void loop() {
  static char buf[7000];
  int pos = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    pos += snprintf(buf + pos, sizeof(buf) - pos, "%d,", i);
  }
  Serial.println(pos);
  Serial.println("Free heap: " + String(ESP.getFreeHeap()));
  delay(100);
}
```

**Monitor heap health:**
```cpp
Serial.printf("Free heap: %d | Min ever: %d\n",
  ESP.getFreeHeap(), ESP.getMinFreeHeap());
```
If `MinFreeHeap` is below ~10KB, your code will eventually crash.

