output:
There are two bugs in this I2C EEPROM code:

**Bug 1: Single-byte address (works for EEPROM < 256 bytes)**
Most I2C EEPROMs (AT24C32/64/128/256) use a **two-byte address**. Sending only 1 byte sets the high address byte to 0 accidentally. For AT24Cxx EEPROMs with >256 bytes:
```cpp
void writeEEPROM(uint16_t addr, byte data) {
  Wire.beginTransmission(EEPROM_ADDR);
  Wire.write((addr >> 8) & 0xFF); // high byte of address
  Wire.write(addr & 0xFF);        // low byte of address
  Wire.write(data);
  Wire.endTransmission();
  delay(5); // EEPROM write cycle time (5–10ms)
}
byte readEEPROM(uint16_t addr) {
  Wire.beginTransmission(EEPROM_ADDR);
  Wire.write((addr >> 8) & 0xFF);
  Wire.write(addr & 0xFF);
  Wire.endTransmission(false); // repeated start (don't release bus)
  Wire.requestFrom(EEPROM_ADDR, 1);
  if (Wire.available()) return Wire.read();
  return 0xFF; // error
}
```

**Bug 2: Missing write cycle delay**
I2C EEPROMs need 5–10ms to complete internal write before next access. `delay(10)` in setup() is correct, but it must be inside or right after `writeEEPROM()`, not in the calling code.

**Bug 3: endTransmission() on read — use false**
To do a repeated start (required for EEPROM random read), use `endTransmission(false)` to keep the bus active between address write and data read.

