output:
The server stops responding due to **heap exhaustion from dynamic String concatenation in handleRequest()**.

**Root cause:** Building a String with 10,000 concatenations allocates ~50KB+ of heap. After a few requests, the heap is too fragmented or exhausted to allocate the response String, `server.send()` fails silently, and the server stops working.

**Fix 1 – Use streaming/chunked response:**
```cpp
void handleRequest() {
  WiFiClient client = server.client();
  server.setContentLength(CONTENT_LENGTH_UNKNOWN);
  server.send(200, "text/plain", "");
  for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    server.sendContent(String(i) + "\n");
    // sendContent sends immediately without buffering
  }
  server.sendContent(""); // end chunked transfer
}
```

**Fix 2 – Use char buffer with pre-allocation:**
```cpp
void handleRequest() {
  const int BUFSIZE = 1024;
  char buf[BUFSIZE];
  server.setContentLength(CONTENT_LENGTH_UNKNOWN);
  server.send(200, "text/plain", "");
  int written = 0;
  int pos = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    pos += snprintf(buf + pos, BUFSIZE - pos, "%d\n", i);
    if (pos > BUFSIZE - 20) {
      server.sendContent(String(buf));
      pos = 0;
    }
  }
  if (pos > 0) server.sendContent(String(buf));
}
```

