Problem: On ESP32, SoftwareSerial (from the EspSoftwareSerial library) is interrupt-driven and can drop bytes if other interrupts (WiFi, BLE, etc.) preempt it. Even at 9600 baud, GPS NMEA sentences are up to 82 characters and must be received without loss for TinyGPS++ to successfully parse them.

Fix: Use ESP32 HardwareSerial for reliable reception:
```cpp
#include <HardwareSerial.h>
HardwareSerial gpsSerial(1); // UART1

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  gpsSerial.begin(9600, SERIAL_8N1, 5, 16); // RX pin 5, TX pin 16
}

void loop() {
  while(gpsSerial.available() > 0)
    if(gps.encode(gpsSerial.read()))
      displayInfo();
}
```
HardwareSerial uses dedicated UART hardware with its own FIFO buffer, making it immune to software interrupt conflicts.

