StaticJsonDocument<20> allocates 20 bytes of stack memory for the JSON document tree. For a single float key-value pair like {"dust": 123.45}, the serialized JSON string is approximately 16-17 characters, so 20 bytes is marginally sufficient. However, this is fragile: if the float value has more decimal digits (e.g. {"dust": 1234.567}), or if more fields are added, both the document and the char buffer[20] will overflow silently, corrupting memory or truncating the JSON. The char buffer must be at least as large as the longest possible serialized string. A safer practice is to use larger sizes:
```cpp
StaticJsonDocument<128> doc;
doc["dust"] = density;
char buffer[128];
serializeJson(doc, buffer);
```
For runtime size calculation you can use ArduinoJson Assistant at arduinojson.org.

