output:
Potential issue: Without an explicit setRotation() in setup(), the TFT will use whatever default rotation is defined in the TFT_eSPI User_Setup.h configuration file (typically 0 = portrait). The benchmarks in setup() run at the default rotation which may not match the physical mounting of the display, so text and graphics could appear sideways or upside-down depending on the hardware.

Fix: Add an explicit rotation call in setup() before running benchmarks:
```cpp
void setup() {
  tft.init();
  tft.setRotation(1); // or 3 for landscape, adjust to your hardware
  tft.fillScreen(TFT_BLACK);
  // ... benchmarks
}
```
The loop() rotation demo is fine as-is since it intentionally cycles all four orientations.

