output:
The issue is that UpdateDustSensorValue() includes a delayMicroseconds(280) for sensor timing plus the Filter() computation, and the HTTP request follows synchronously. While this is not typically problematic (280us is tiny), the larger concern is that the 2000ms delay blocks everything, including WiFi background processing.

Improved non-blocking structure:
```cpp
unsigned long lastRead = 0;
unsigned long lastSend = 0;
float latestDensity = 0;

void loop() {
  // Read sensor every 500ms
  if(millis() - lastRead >= 500) {
    lastRead = millis();
    latestDensity = readDustDensity(); // Returns float
  }
  // Send to Firebase every 2000ms
  if(millis() - lastSend >= 2000 && WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED) {
    lastSend = millis();
    sendToFirebase(latestDensity);
  }
}
```
This separates sensor reading from network transmission, keeps the loop non-blocking, and allows WiFi stack tasks to run continuously.

